WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:13.656
Before the simulator can tell you anything useful, you
have to tell it the exact rules you're playing by. This
top section is where you do that. Get it wrong here, and
every number below is fiction.

2
00:00:14.256 --> 00:00:30.504
Start with your prop firm. Apex, Topstep, Take Profit,
Lucid, and the rest. Pick yours and it auto-loads that
firm's account size, eval cost, and profit split. The
presets are just a starting point though. If your firm
tweaked its rules, edit the numbers to match exactly.

3
00:00:31.104 --> 00:00:46.752
These three set the economics. Account size is the balance
you're evaluated on. Eval cost is what you actually paid
for the attempt. And profit split is the slice of profit
you keep once you're funded. Get these right and every
dollar figure below becomes real money, not a guess.

4
00:00:47.352 --> 00:01:02.040
Simulations is how many times it replays your history. Two
thousand is plenty. Resample draws your trades at random
with replacement. Shuffle just reorders the ones you
actually had. Resample explores more what-ifs. Shuffle
stays closer to what really happened.

5
00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:17.832
Then the rulebook itself. Target is the profit you need.
Max DD is the drawdown that busts you. Daily loss is the
intraday cap. Min and max days are the window you have to
do it in. Change any one of these and the whole simulation
re-runs against the new rule.

6
00:01:18.432 --> 00:01:35.424
And the one setting beginners get wrong. Drawdown mode.
Trailing follows your highest balance upward, so even
handing back profit can bust you. Static only measures
from your starting balance. Trailing is harsher, and it's
the classic funded-account rule. Set it to match your
firm, or every number lies to you.

7
00:01:36.024 --> 00:01:42.960
Set the rules once, and set them honestly. Everything the
simulator tells you from here is only as true as these
inputs.
